1 Introduction and learning objectives

The purpose of this exercise is to build an estimation engine to guide investment decisions in London house market. You will first build machine learning algorithms (and tune them) to estimate the house prices given variety of information about each property. Then, using your algorithm, you will choose 200 houses to invest in out of about 2000 houses on the market at the moment.

Learning objectives

  1. Using different data mining algorithms for prediction.
  2. Dealing with large data sets
  3. Tuning data mining algorithms
  4. Interpreting data mining algorithms and deducing importance of variables
  5. Using results of data mining algorithms to make business decisions

2 Load data

There are two sets of data, i) training data that has the actual prices ii) out of sample data that has the asking prices. Load both data sets.

Make sure you understand what information each column contains. Note that not all information provided might be useful in predicting house prices, but do not make any assumptions before you decide what information you use in your prediction algorithms.

# Fix dates

  train_data <- train_data %>% mutate(date = as.Date(date, "%Y-%m-%d"))
}
if("date" %in% colnames(test_data)) {
  test_data <- test_data %>% mutate(date = as.Date(date, "%Y-%m-%d"))
}

# Convert character variables to factor
train_data <- train_data %>%
  mutate(across(where(is.character), as.factor))

test_data <- test_data %>%
  mutate(across(where(is.character), as.factor))

# Drop columns if they are not useful or have too many missing values
train_data <- train_data %>% select(-address2, -town, -date) 
test_data <- test_data %>% select(-address2, -town, -date)

# Impute missing values in `population` if it exists
if("population" %in% colnames(train_data)){
  train_data$population[is.na(train_data$population)] <- median(train_data$population, na.rm = TRUE)
}
if("population" %in% colnames(test_data)){
  test_data$population[is.na(test_data$population)] <- median(test_data$population, na.rm = TRUE)
}

# produce a correlation table using GGally::ggcor()
# this takes a while to plot
# keep Y variable last

train_data %>% 
  ggcorr(method = c("pairwise", "pearson"), layout.exp = 2,label_round=2, label = TRUE,label_size = 2,hjust = 1,nbreaks = 5,size = 2,angle = -20)

numeric_data <- train_data %>% select(where(is.numeric))

# Compute correlation matrix
cor_matrix <- cor(numeric_data, use = "pairwise.complete.obs", method = "pearson")

# Extract correlations with 'price'
price_corr <- cor_matrix["price", ]

# Sort by absolute correlation, descending order
top_vars <- names(sort(abs(price_corr), decreasing = TRUE))

# Remove 'price' itself
top_vars <- top_vars[top_vars != "price"]

# Print top correlated variables
print(top_vars)

5 Fit a tree model

Next I fit a tree model using the same subset of features. Again you can (and should) add more variables and tune the parameter of your tree to find a better fit.

Compare the performance of the linear regression model with the tree model; which one performs better? Why do you think that is the case?

### Feature Engineering ###
training_set <- training_set %>% mutate(log_price = log(price))
validation_set <- validation_set %>% mutate(log_price = log(price))

# rooms_per_area
training_set <- training_set %>%
  mutate(rooms_per_area = number_habitable_rooms / (total_floor_area + 1))
validation_set <- validation_set %>%
  mutate(rooms_per_area = number_habitable_rooms / (total_floor_area + 1))

# distance_to_center
center_lat <- 51.5074
center_lon <- -0.1278
training_set <- training_set %>%
  mutate(distance_to_center = sqrt((latitude - center_lat)^2 + (longitude - center_lon)^2))
validation_set <- validation_set %>%
  mutate(distance_to_center = sqrt((latitude - center_lat)^2 + (longitude - center_lon)^2))

# log_distance_station
training_set <- training_set %>%
  mutate(log_distance_station = log(distance_to_station + 1))
validation_set <- validation_set %>%
  mutate(log_distance_station = log(distance_to_station + 1))

# log_energy_consumption_current
training_set <- training_set %>%
  mutate(log_energy_consumption_current = log(energy_consumption_current + 1))
validation_set <- validation_set %>%
  mutate(log_energy_consumption_current = log(energy_consumption_current + 1))

# Check that these variables exist
missing_in_train <- setdiff(top_vars, colnames(training_set))
if(length(missing_in_train) > 0){
  stop("The following variables are missing in training_set: ", paste(missing_in_train, collapse=", "))
}

# final_vars includes chosen predictors only (no log_price as predictor)
final_vars <- top_vars  # only the top_vars, exclude "log_price" from predictors


# Include log_price separately as the outcome, not as a predictor
training_set <- training_set %>% select(all_of(final_vars), log_price)
validation_set <- validation_set %>% select(all_of(final_vars), log_price)

validation_set$price <- validation_set_original$price

  log_price ~ .,

  trControl = control,
  tuneLength=10
    )

Use at least two other algorithms to predict prices. Dont forget to tune the parameters of these algorithms. And then compare the performances of your algorithms to linear regression and trees.

## RANDOM FOREST ##


set.seed(123)
control_min <- trainControl(method = "cv", number = 2, savePredictions = "final")

tune_grid_expanded <- expand.grid(
  mtry = c(3,5,7),
  splitrule = "variance",
  min.node.size = c(5,10)
)

# Using entire Training Set
model_rf_min <- train(
  log_price ~ ., # Excluding price, only use predictors and log_price as the target
  data = training_set,
  method = "ranger",
  trControl = control_min,
  tuneGrid = tune_grid_expanded,
  num.trees = 200,
  importance = 'impurity'
)

print(model_rf_min)

  RMSE = RMSE(predictions, validation_set$price),
  R2 = R2(predictions, validation_set$price)

set.seed(123)
control_xgb <- trainControl(
  method = "cv", 
  number = 5,             
  verboseIter = TRUE,     # See progress
  savePredictions = "final"
)

# Tuning grid for XGBoost:
# - nrounds: number of boosting iterations
# - max_depth: depth of each tree
# - eta: learning rate
# - gamma: minimum loss reduction required to make a split
# - colsample_bytree: subsample ratio of columns
# - min_child_weight: minimum sum of instance weight needed in a child

tune_grid_xgb <- expand.grid(
  nrounds = c(100, 200),
  max_depth = c(3, 5),
  eta = c(0.1, 0.05),
  gamma = c(0, 1),
  colsample_bytree = c(0.8),
  min_child_weight = c(1),
  subsample = c(0.8) 
)

model_xgb <- train(
  log_price ~ .,
  data = training_set,
  method = "xgbTree",
  trControl = control_xgb,
  tuneGrid = tune_grid_xgb,
  metric = "RMSE"
)

control_gbm <- trainControl(
  method = "cv",
  number = 5,
  savePredictions = "final",    
  verboseIter = TRUE
)

  interaction.depth = c(3, 5),
  n.trees = c(100, 200),        
  shrinkage = c(0.1, 0.05),     # Learning rate
  n.minobsinnode = c(5, 10)
)

model_gbm <- train(
  log_price ~ .,
  data = training_set,
  method = "gbm",
  trControl = control_gbm,
  tuneGrid = tune_grid_gbm,
  metric = "RMSE",
  verbose = FALSE
)

7 Stacking

Use stacking to ensemble your algorithms.

# 3. Model Stacking (Ensembling)
##############################

# With savePredictions = "final"
models_list <- list(
  rf = model_rf_min,
  xgb = model_xgb,
  gbm = model_gbm
)

# Trains the stacked model
stacked_model <- caretStack(
  models_list,
  method = "lm",       
  metric = "RMSE",
  trControl = trainControl(method = "cv", number = 5)
)
## Warning: Attempting to coerce all.models to a caretList.
print(stacked_model)

validation_set$price <- as.numeric(as.character(validation_set$price))

# Predictions from stacked model
# Returns a data frame with a column named "pred"
predictions_log_stack_df <- predict(stacked_model, validation_set)
# Extracts the numeric vector from the data frame
predictions_log_stack <- predictions_log_stack_df$pred

# Exponentiate to return predictions OG price scale
predictions_stack <- exp(predictions_log_stack)

# RMSE and R
stack_results <- data.frame(
  RMSE = RMSE(predictions_stack, validation_set$price),
  R2 = R2(predictions_stack, validation_set$price)
)

print(stack_results)

8 Pick investments

In this section you should use the best algorithm you identified to choose 200 properties from the out of sample data.

# Added columns (rooms_per_area, distance_to_center, etc.) to test_data
# Do NOT drop the original columns.
test_data <- test_data %>%
  mutate(
    rooms_per_area = number_habitable_rooms / (total_floor_area + 1),
    distance_to_center = sqrt((latitude - 51.5074)^2 + (longitude + 0.1278)^2),
    log_distance_station = log(distance_to_station + 1),
    log_energy_consumption_current = log(energy_consumption_current + 1)
  ) %>% 
  select(all_of(final_vars), asking_price)


# Predict with stacked_model
predictions_log_test_df <- predict(stacked_model, test_data)
predictions_log_test <- predictions_log_test_df$pred
test_data$predicted_price <- exp(predictions_log_test)

# Profit Calculation
test_data$profit <- (test_data$predicted_price - test_data$asking_price) / test_data$asking_price

# Sort by profit and pick top 200
test_data <- test_data %>% arrange(desc(profit))
test_data$buy <- 0
test_data$buy[1:200] <- 1

#Output your choices. Change the name of the file to your "lastname_firstname.csv"
#Kept all columns
write.csv(test_data, "Zaidi_Uzair.csv", row.names = FALSE)
